cs.PL, cs.AR, cs.LO, cs.DC, cs.SE 

This paper is likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category as it provides the syntax and semantics of a parallel assembly language. It may also belong to the Architecture (cs.AR) sub-category as it discusses an Instruction Set Architecture. Additionally, it could be classified under Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) as it provides analytic semantics. Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) is another possible sub-category as the language is designed for simulating weak consistency models. Finally, Software Engineering (cs.SE) is a possible sub-category as the language is implemented in a tool for simulation.
